lace, Suite 330, Boston, MA  02111-1307  USA\\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\\npackage gnu.io;\\n\\n/**\\nA class to keep the current version in\\n*/\\n\\npublic class RXTXVersion\\n{\\n/*------------------------------------------------------------------------------\\n\\tRXTXVersion  \\n\\taccept:       -\\n\\tperform:      Set Version.\\n\\treturn:       -\\n\\texceptions:   Throwable\\n\\tcomments:     \\n\\t\\t      See INSTALL for details.\\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------*/\\n\\tprivate static String Version;\\n\\n\\tstatic {\\n\\t\\tSystem.loadLibrary( \\\"rxtxSerial\\\" );\\n\\t\\tVersion = \\\"RXTX-2.1-7\\\";\\n\\t}\\n\\t/**\\n\\t*  static method to return the current version of RXTX\\n\\t*  unique to RXTX.\\n\\t*  @returns a string representing the version  \\\"RXTX-1.4-9\\\"\\n\\t*/\\n\\tpublic static String getVersion()\\n\\t{\\n\\t\\treturn(Version);\\n\\t}\\n\\tpublic static native String nativeGetVersion();\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777799920922}]}\n1459:[thinking] I'm considering whether I can avoid static initialization of RXTXCommDriver by adding a placeholder class in the test classpath. It seems the Gradle test runtime prioritizes test classes, but having a fake class in package gnu.io might violate the testing guidelines. I wonder if including a fake native library using Java can work, but it feels complex. Also, I need to ensure that tests don't fail in different environments, so I must strategize carefully.\n1461:[thinking] **Exploring error handling in dynamic loading**\n1463:[thinking] I'm thinking about whether I can catch errors specifically related to unsupported dynamic class loading. It might not be as relevant as I initially thought. I wonder if a native image actually executes System.loadLibrary, and it turns out it does, provided I have a dummy or stub library on the path. I could potentially include a real C stub source